00:11:57.930 --> 00:12:00.530
The point is that in order
to resolve the photon

00:12:00.530 --> 00:12:02.520
distributions at
the screen, you need

00:12:02.520 --> 00:12:04.630
to know which
detector was triggered

00:12:04.630 --> 00:12:08.530
by every one of those
photon's entangled twins.

00:12:08.530 --> 00:12:11.710
This is done with
coincidence electronics.

00:12:11.710 --> 00:12:14.220
If we see exactly
the right time offset

00:12:14.220 --> 00:12:17.790
between a hit on the screen and
a hit at one of the detectors,

00:12:17.790 --> 00:12:21.110
that means that those two
photons were an entangled pair.

00:12:21.110 --> 00:12:24.900
After the experiment is done,
we can pick out off the screen

00:12:24.900 --> 00:12:28.520
all of the photons that had
twins hitting, say, detector

00:12:28.520 --> 00:12:33.210
A. Those photons turn out to
show no interference pattern.

00:12:33.210 --> 00:12:36.490
But the photons
associated with C or D

00:12:36.490 --> 00:12:38.180
do have an interference pattern.

00:12:38.180 --> 00:12:40.490
However, there is
no way to figure out

00:12:40.490 --> 00:12:43.420
which photons correspond
to which detectors

00:12:43.420 --> 00:12:46.140
until the arrival
times at the screen

00:12:46.140 --> 00:12:49.720
are compared to the arrival
times at the other detectors.

