And that information
has to be sent

00:12:52.150 --> 00:12:55.450
at regular,
slower-than-light speeds.

00:12:55.450 --> 00:12:58.360
In a way, this is
even more crazy.

00:12:58.360 --> 00:13:01.630
Those locations are
recorded on the screen,

00:13:01.630 --> 00:13:04.970
and the interference patterns
are embedded in them.

00:13:04.970 --> 00:13:07.520
Those interference
patterns hold information

00:13:07.520 --> 00:13:09.330
about future events.

00:13:09.330 --> 00:13:11.660
But we can't extract
that information

00:13:11.660 --> 00:13:13.980
until those future
events have occurred,

00:13:13.980 --> 00:13:17.860
and we can compare notes between
the screen and detectors.

00:13:17.860 --> 00:13:20.610
We'll go into all of this in
more detail in the challenge

00:13:20.610 --> 00:13:23.560
question answer and also
when we come back to quantum

00:13:23.560 --> 00:13:24.550
entanglement.

00:13:24.550 --> 00:13:26.360
On a related note,
David Stagg would

00:13:26.360 --> 00:13:28.820
like to know what the
interference screen looks

00:13:28.820 --> 00:13:33.040
like before you know what the
data is at detectors A, B, C,

00:13:33.040 --> 00:13:37.040
and D. Well, the screen just
looks like a blur of photons.

00:13:37.040 --> 00:13:40.970
You see, it's not just that
the blur of photons connected

00:13:40.970 --> 00:13:44.980
to detectors A and B are
overlaid with an interference

00:13:44.980 --> 00:13:47.060
pattern from C and D, no.

00:13:47.060 --> 00:13:51.290
Even C and D produce
a blur until you

00:13:51.290 --> 00:13:53.520
compare coincidence data.

00:13:53.520 --> 00:13:55.460
As I mentioned in the
challenge question,

00:13:55.460 --> 00:13:59.080
the interference pattern
of C has the opposite phase

00:13:59.080 --> 00:14:03.350
to that of D. Its peaks line
up with D's valleys and vice

00:14:03.350 --> 00:14:04.160
versa.

00:14:04.160 --> 00:14:06.640
It's like adding a
sign in a cosine wave.

00:14:06.640 --> 00:14:08.680
It adds up to a
flat distribution,

00:14:08.680 --> 00:14:10.870
and it's only when you look
at the photons connected

00:14:10.870 --> 00:14:14.672
to C and D separately
that you see the bands.

